wxWidgets 2.8.12: build with a modern GCC 10 / MinGW-w64 (compilation patch).

Needed by every GUI build (full-rebuild, and the IRC 0.1.0/0.1.3 clients).
This is a COMPILATION patch (modern-toolchain fix), not a change to Satoshi's
code.

wxWidgets 2.8.12 (2011) predates GCC 10. Two issues arise; only ONE needs a
source edit:

  1. _mkdir / _rmdir  (THIS patch, required).
     include/wx/filefn.h maps the POSIX file ops through wxPOSIX_IDENT, which
     uses the underscore spellings (_mkdir, _rmdir) for every compiler except
     __MINGW64__. A 32-bit MinGW-w64 toolchain defines only __MINGW32__, so it
     takes the underscore branch — but those symbols live in <direct.h>, which
     filefn.h does not include. Pull it in for 32-bit MinGW.

  2. narrowing of `case -1:` over a DWORD in src/msw/utilsexc.cpp.
     This is NOT a wxWidgets bug: it only fires because GCC 10 defaults to a
     newer C++ standard (gnu++14), where braced/`case` narrowing is an error.
     Build wxWidgets in its native standard and it disappears — NO source edit,
     NO -Wno-narrowing hack:
         CXXFLAGS="-std=gnu++98 -fpermissive -w"
     (Verified: wxWidgets 2.8.12 builds clean this way with only fix #1.)
     `-Wno-narrowing` is a fallback only if you insist on a newer -std.

The third fix some guides mention (__atomic_compare_exchange in Berkeley DB 4.8)
belongs to Berkeley DB, not wxWidgets — see berkeley-db-4.8-gcc-atomic.patch.
It is only needed on build paths that link Berkeley DB.

Apply from inside the wxWidgets-2.8.12 source tree:
    patch -p1 < wxWidgets-2.8.12-mingw.patch

--- a/include/wx/filefn.h
+++ b/include/wx/filefn.h
@@ -203,6 +203,13 @@

     // functions

+    // mingw fix: on 32-bit MinGW-w64 only __MINGW32__ is defined, so
+    // wxPOSIX_IDENT uses the underscore spellings (_mkdir/_rmdir) which live in
+    // <direct.h> — pull it in so they are declared.
+    #if defined(__MINGW32__) && !defined(__MINGW64__)
+        #include <direct.h>
+    #endif
+
     // MSVC and compatible compilers prepend underscores to the POSIX function
     // names, other compilers don't and even if their later versions usually do
     // define the versions with underscores for MSVC compatibility, it's better
